Historically, ''left-dot-sin'' corresponds to [[Proto-Semitic language|Proto-Semitic]] *{{transl|sem|ś}}, which in biblical-Judaic-Hebrew corresponded to the [[Voiceless dental and alveolar lateral fricatives|voiceless alveolar lateral fricative]] {{IPA|/ɬ/}}, as evidenced in the Greek transliteration of Hebrew words such as ''[[balsam]]'' ({{Hebrew|בֹּשֶׂם}}) (the ''ls'' - 'שׂ') as is evident in the ''[[Targum Onkelos]]''.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}}

====Dagesh====

{{main|Dagesh}}
Historically, the consonants {{hebrew|ב}} ''beth'', {{hebrew|ג}} ''gimel'', {{hebrew|ד}} ''daleth'', {{hebrew|כ}} ''kaf'', {{hebrew|פ}} ''pe'' and {{hebrew|ת}} ''tav'' each had two sounds: one hard ([[plosive]]), and one soft ([[fricative consonant|fricative]]), depending on the position of the letter and other factors. When vowel diacritics are used, the hard sounds are indicated by a central dot called ''dagesh'' ({{hebrew|דגש}}), while the soft sounds lack a ''dagesh''. In modern Hebrew, however, the ''dagesh'' only changes the pronunciation of {{hebrew|ב}} ''beth'', {{hebrew|כ}} ''kaf'', and {{hebrew|פ}} ''pe'', and does not affect the name of the letter.  The differences are as follows:

